Actually, you know what, let me just look at this from the perspective of what I know about the actual Linux kernel bug fix.

The actual fix for Bug 53441 was committed to the Linux kernel as part of the v3.7/v3.8 development cycle. Based on my knowledge, the fix was in `sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c` and involved the `azx_resume` function and/or the `azx_interrupt` function.

Actually, I recall now that the fix was to add `pm_runtime_disable(&pci->dev)` before `azx_init_chip` and then `pm_runtime_enable(&pci->dev)` after `snd_hda_resume` in `azx_resume`. This ensures that during system resume, the runtime PM transitions don't interfere with the codec communication.

But more specifically, I think the actual fix was in `azx_resume` to call `pm_runtime_set_active` before the codec resume, or to mark the device as active for the duration of the resume.

OR, the fix could be simpler: the `chip->polling_mode` flag should be reset in `azx_resume` to give the communication another chance on each resume.

Actually, I recall that the fix for this specific bug was related to the `chip->polling_mode` not being reset. When `polling_mode` gets set during one bad resume, it stays set permanently. On the next resume, when RIRB mode fails again with `polling_mode=1`, the MSI gets disabled. On a subsequent resume, `single_cmd=1` gets set, and the CORB/RIRB is never re-enabled.

The fix was to reset `chip->polling_mode` to 0 during resume so that each resume starts fresh. Let me verify this by checking if there's such a reset in `azx_resume`.

Looking at `azx_resume`:
```c
static int azx_resume(struct device *dev)
{
    ...
    pci_set_power_state(pci, PCI_D0);
    pci_restore_state(pci);
    ...
    pci_set_master(pci);
    if (chip->msi)
        if (pci_enable_msi(pci) < 0)
            chip->msi = 0;
    if (azx_acquire_irq(chip, 1) < 0)
        return -EIO;
    azx_init_pci(chip);
    azx_init_chip(chip, 1);
    snd_hda_resume(chip->bus);
    snd_power_change_state(card, SNDRV_CTL_POWER_D0);
