{
  "buggy_files": [
    "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c"
  ],
  "buggy_functions": [
    {
      "file": "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c",
      "function": "azx_interrupt",
      "lines": "1317-1320",
      "reason": "PRIMARY BUG: The runtime PM guard `if (chip->pci->dev.power.runtime_status != RPM_ACTIVE) return IRQ_NONE` (introduced in 3.7 for CONFIG_PM_RUNTIME) fires during system resume. When the device was runtime-PM-suspended before system sleep (state = RPM_SUSPENDED), the system PM resume path calls azx_init_chip() then snd_hda_resume() without ever restoring runtime_status to RPM_ACTIVE. Every RIRB response interrupt triggered by codec communication during snd_hda_resume() is therefore silently dropped, causing azx_rirb_get_response() to time out. This is the direct trigger of the observed failure cascade."
    },
    {
      "file": "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c",
      "function": "azx_resume",
      "lines": "2539-2566",
      "reason": "CONTRIBUTING BUG: azx_resume() re-initialises the controller hardware (azx_init_chip) and then immediately calls snd_hda_resume() to communicate with codecs, but it never restores the PCI device's runtime PM state to RPM_ACTIVE before doing so. When the controller was runtime-PM-suspended before system sleep (runtime_status = RPM_SUSPENDED), this means all RIRB interrupts raised during snd_hda_resume() are discarded by azx_interrupt(). The fix requires marking the device as PM-active (e.g. pm_runtime_set_active / pm_runtime_disable+enable) before codec communication. Additionally, azx_resume() does not reset accumulated error-mode flags (chip->poll_count, chip->polling_mode, chip->msi, chip->single_cmd) that degrade the command interface across successive suspend/resume cycles."
    },
    {
      "file": "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c",
      "function": "azx_init_cmd_io",
      "lines": "743-746",
      "reason": "CONTRIBUTING BUG: After writing ICH6_CORBRP_RST (bit 15) to the CORBRP register to reset the CORB read pointer (line 744), the reset bit is never cleared back to 0. The Intel HDA specification requires software to explicitly clear CORBRPRST to 0 and verify the clear before starting CORB DMA. On some hardware this bit does not auto-clear, leaving CORB DMA in a reset-held state and preventing commands from being dispatched to the codec. Even when polling mode is active (chip->polling_mode = 1), commands are not delivered to the codec, causing RIRB polls to time out and accelerating the fallback to MSI-disable and ultimately single_cmd mode across successive resumes."
    },
    {
      "file": "sound/pci/hda/hda_intel.c",
      "function": "azx_rirb_get_response",
      "lines": "863-958",
      "reason": "FAILURE PROPAGATION: chip->poll_count is incremented each time a fallback do_poll attempt is needed but is only reset to 0 on a clean (non-do_poll) response. Because the first RIRB interrupt failure on each resume increments poll_count without resetting it, poll_count accumulates across multiple suspend/resume cycles. Once poll_count reaches 2, the function permanently sets chip->polling_mode = 1. Further timeouts then permanently disable MSI and finally set chip->single_cmd = 1 (which suppresses azx_init_cmd_io() on all subsequent resumes via azx_init_chip()), making the audio hardware unrecoverable until reboot."
    }
  ],
  "root_cause_summary": "Bug introduced in v3.7.1 by assigning AZX_DCAPS_INTEL_PCH (which includes AZX_DCAPS_PM_RUNTIME) to the Intel 5 Series/3400 HDA device (PCI 0x8086:0x3b56, line 3488-3489). This enabled runtime PM for the controller for the first time. When the controller is runtime-PM-suspended before system sleep, the device's PCI runtime_status is RPM_SUSPENDED. On system wake, azx_resume() re-initialises the hardware and calls snd_hda_resume() to restore codecs, but azx_interrupt() returns IRQ_NONE for every RIRB response interrupt because runtime_status != RPM_ACTIVE. Codec communication times out, incrementally ratcheting chip->poll_count → chip->polling_mode → MSI disabled → chip->single_cmd across successive suspend/resume cycles until audio is permanently broken.",
